&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence from 
[normal]David Bridge
[normal] (CYS0081)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Thank you for your invitation to send in my views on cycling safety. These are my views. Whether this makes it evidence I don't know.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1. Is Cycling, especially urban cycling safe[bold]Nothing totally safe in the real world. In fact urban cycling is safer on a
[normal] per mile basis than rural cycling. I am told that cycling is about as safe per mile as being a pedestrian; 
[normal]We
[normal] just worry about cycling more. As it puts up your life expectancy it can't be that dangerous. 69 or so pedestrians were killed in London last yea
[normal]r. Has any fuss been made about that? Most of those who call cycling too dangerous seem just to want cyclists off the roads.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]One oft-forgotten issue is that cycling along rural 
[normal]A
[normal] roads is particularly dangerous. Some thought should be given to installing 
[normal]cycle-ways on these whenever building new ones. Here at least there are few pedestrians to clash with.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2[bold] What central and local Government could [bold]do[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.[bold] Whether it would be desirable and feasible to segregate cyclists from other road users, including, for example, by prohibiting HGVs f[bold]rom entering city centres at peak hours[bold]&#xa0;
